### Hugging Face

Hugging Face es un repositorio de modelos, datasets y aplicaciones generativas al que cualquier persona puede subir sus modelos. Para esta pr√°ctica debe registrarse y obtener una API Key (en Hugging Face se llama Access Token). Esta API Key hay que crearla con permisos de escritura.

### Google Colab

Es un servicio de Google que puede alojar y ejecutar libros de Jupyter. Es una interesante combinaci√≥n con Hugging Face porque permite ejecutar modelos LLM con GPU. Esta pr√°ctica debe ser ejecutada con una GPU, as√≠ que si no dispone de una, debe ejecutarla dentro de Google Colab. Es importante que est√© seleccionado un procesador GPU dentro de Colab. La API key de Hugging Face debe ponerla en el apartado de secretos (üîë) de la izquierda y  pulsar "habilitar el acceso desde el cuaderno". No es una buena idea copiarla en una celda.

    If there's one thing I want you to remember about using HuggingFace pipelines, it's that there are a few options that you can use. The first one is to use the custom feature to export a list of labels, which is a very powerful feature. Another option is to use the 'auto' feature to export a list of labels that can be customized in a fashion that seems natural. For example, if you're using a custom list (such as list.com), you can also export a list with a single label.
    
    There are two other options that you can use to export a list of labels. The first is to export a list of labels in a different format to the new format. To do this, simply add the following to your export.hpp file:
    
    export default {'my-label' :'my-label' ; }
    
    The second option is to export a list of labels using the custom feature. For example, if you're exporting a list of labels in a different format, try exporting the new format in a different format. The custom feature is just a shortcut to the custom feature that can be exported as a command line option.
    
    When you're done exporting, you can export the list of labels with the same command line option.

```python
# Audio Generation

synthesiser = pipeline("text-to-speech", "microsoft/speecht5_tts", device='cuda')

embeddings_dataset = load_dataset("Matthijs/cmu-arctic-xvectors", split="validation")
speaker_embedding = torch.tensor(embeddings_dataset[7306]["xvector"]).unsqueeze(0)

speech = synthesiser("Hi to an artificial intelligence engineer, on the way to mastery!", forward_params={"speaker_embeddings": speaker_embedding})

sf.write("speech.wav", speech["audio"], samplerate=speech["sampling_rate"])
Audio("speech.wav")
```
